":null,"system":{},"sort":2700000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"name":"Crew Templates","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"mmDemo-logo\"><img style=\"border:0\" src=\"modules/pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo/art/MM.png\" /></div><div class=\"main-box\"><h4 class=\"mimic-h1\">Crew Templates</h4><hr /><p style=\"width:90%\">The full version of Mercenary Marketplace contains crew templates which can be used to automatically turn any NPC in your collection into a Crew of 4 to 6 individuals working in unison.</p><p style=\"width:90%\">These templates will grant the Crew trait. Any creature with the Crew trait is treated as a single creature for the purposes of spells and effects. However, it may be selected twice for abilities that require you to select two adjacent creatures, such as swipe.</p><p>Below you will find a description of how to use the templates in the full of the module.</p><h2 class=\"stylish\">Instructions</h2><div style=\"width:90%;margin:0 auto\"><h3 class=\"dark\">Step 1. Select Template</h3><p>Select a Crew Template. There are two Crew Templates provided.</p><p>The <strong>Ragtag Crew Template</strong> which produces a Crew with a level 2-higher than that of the base creature.</p><p>The <strong>Crew Template</strong> which produces a Crew with a level 4-higher than that of the base creature.</p><h3 class=\"dark\">Step 2. Select Abilities</h3><p>Select Crew Abilities from the table below for your Crew. Select 1 ability if you are creating a Ragtag Crew or 2 if you are creating a standard Crew.</p><p>These abilities represent special training or capabilities the Crew has developed as a group. The abilities have been divided into Universal Abilities that are useful to all Crews, and Spellcaster Exclusive Abilities that are only useful if the base creature is a spellcaster. Please note that Simultaneous Casting and United Casting are mutually exclusive abilities.</p><table style=\"width:100%;border-style:hidden\" border=\"0\"><tbody><tr style=\"height:19px\"><td style=\"width:100%;text-align:center;background-color:#050e18;height:19px\"><strong>Universal Abilities</strong></td></tr></tbody></table><table style=\"width:100%;border-style:hidden\" border=\"0\"><tbody><tr><td style=\"width:50%;color:#050e18\"><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0;text-align:start\"><strong>Back to Back</strong></p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0;text-align:start\"><strong>Bodyguard Training</strong></p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0;text-align:start\"><strong>Collateral Damage</strong></p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0;text-align:start\"><strong>Collective Reflexes</strong></p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0;text-align:start\"><strong>Concentrated Assault</strong></p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0;text-align:start\"><strong>Diversified Strikes</strong></p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0;text-align:start\"><strong>Formation Training</strong></p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0;text-align:start\"><strong>Frontline Protection</strong></p></td><td style=\"width:50%;color:#050e18\"><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0;text-align:start\"><strong>Guarded Retreat</strong></p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0;text-align:start\"><strong>Harrying Vanguard</strong></p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0;text-align:start\"><strong>Perceptive Crew</strong></p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0;text-align:start\"><strong>Reactive Punishment</strong></p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0;text-align:start\"><strong>Scattered Shots</strong></p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0;text-align:start\"><strong>Shared Defence</strong></p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0;text-align:start\"><strong>Skilled Teamwork</strong></p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0;text-align:start\"><strong>Team Flanking</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><table style=\"width:100%;border-style:hidden\" border=\"0\"><tbody><tr style=\"height:19px\"><td style=\"width:100%;text-align:center;background-color:#050e18;height:19px\"><strong>Spellcaster Exclusive Abilities</strong></td></tr></tbody></table><table style=\"width:100%;border-style:hidden\" border=\"0\"><tbody><tr><td style=\"width:50%;color:#050e18\"><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0;text-align:start\"><strong>Collaborative Sustain</strong></p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0;text-align:start\"><strong>Joint Summoning</strong></p></td><td style=\"width:50%;color:#050e18\"><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0;text-align:start\"><strong>Simultaneous Casting</strong></p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0;text-align:start\"><strong>United Casting</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><h3 class=\"dark\">Step 3. Apply Template</h3><p>Apply your selected Crew Template from Step 1 by dragging it to the NPC token or character sheet of your choice. After you have dropped it on the token or sheet, you will need to answer a prompt asking you the size of the base creature you have applied the template to. Once you have input the base creature's size, subsequent prompts will pop up asking which abilities you would like to add to your new Crew. Each prompt will present a dropdown of all of the Crew Abilities listed above, in alphabetical order. After you have made your selection(s) the template will automatically adjust the base creature's statistics, and use the grant item rule element to automatically add your selected crew abilities to the base creature.</p><h3 class=\"dark\">Step 4. Manual Adjustments</h3><p>After applying your Crew Template and selecting your Crew Ability(s), there are a few manual changes you may need to make. Firstly, you will want to update the Crew's current HP to match its new maximum HP. You may also wish to update the base creature's name to reflect that it is now a Crew. If the base creature was a spellcaster, and you have given it Joint Summoning, Simultaneous Casting, or United Casting, you will need to update the creature's spellcasting entries according to the instructions for the relevant Crew Ability. These instructions can be found in the abilities' description tab, and follow the heading, \"template\". You may also find taking a look at some of the spellcasters from @UUID[Compendium.pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-journals.1s34nyLF4vYUxsHX.JournalEntryPage.J5arLCsj7pbrI1eQ]{Crews} a useful example for how each of these three abilities modifies the base creature's spellcasting entries. </p><p><em><strong>Please Note</strong></em><strong> -</strong> While the Crew Template has modified your creature's strikes, current limitations with the NPC sheets for the PF2e system on Foundry mean that the modified values  will not be displayed on the sheet, however the damage adjustment will apply correctly when rolled. </p><h3 class=\"dark\">Step 5. Customization (Optional)</h3><p><strong>Weak and Elite Crews -</strong> If you wish to apply an Elite or Weak template to adjust the strength of your created Crew, that adjustment should be applied now. The way Weak and Elite adjustments are implemented in Foundry VTT the order of application does not matter. You can apply the Weak/Elite adjustment either prior to, or after, applying your Crew Template.</p><p><strong>Crews with Ancestries -</strong> Should you wish to produce a Crew of a particular Ancestry, you may also apply one of the @UUID[Compendium.pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-journals.1s34nyLF4vYUxsHX.JournalEntryPage.QibnMkhhPYrIrwG5]{Ancestry Templates} to your Crew now.</p><p><strong>Additional Crew Abilities - </strong>The Crew templates are designed to increase the power of the base creature to represent the strength of a team of creatures working together. While the number of Crew Abilities granted was selected to provide an adequate bump in power for the increase in level for either version of the template, you may find you wish to create a particularly well-trained or coordinated version of a Crew. In which case, you may wish to add an additional Crew Ability to your new Crew by dragging it from the tables in Step 2. Or, perhaps you wish to create an especially poorly trained Crew. You can accomplish this  by creating a Crew with less Crew Abilities than usual. </p><p><strong>Crews with Descriptive Templates -</strong> The math for Crews has been constructed to scale with the Base Creature's level. If you wish to apply a @UUID[Compendium.pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-journals.1s34nyLF4vYUxsHX.JournalEntryPage.ri8fswkWP7Bimh8l]{Descriptive Templates}, you should apply it first, before applying the Crew template, to ensure the Crew template functions as intended.</p><p><em><strong>Caution</strong></em> - Stacking Crew and Descriptive templates may produce results that are more or less powerful than expected based on the listed level adjustments.</p></div><details><summary class=\"exposition\"><h2 class=\"stylish-summary\">Lore Justification</h2></summary><div style=\"width:90%;background-color:floralwhite;padding:10px 30px;margin-left:5%;margin-top:0px;border-radius:0px 0px 15px 15px\"><p>Why are Crews, groups of 4 to 6 individuals, affected by magic and other effects as if they are a single creature? While I can certainly provide a number of mechanical and balance reasons, I believe that a satisfying answer needs to make sense within the world.</p><p>The default lore for how Crews work is sympathetic magic. By sympathetic magic what I mean is that there is some effect present that makes any magic cast upon on member of the crew resonate through all members of the Crew. I've got several possible explanations for the underlying cause of this sympathetic magic; feel free to pick your favourite for your world, include different explanations for different Crews, or invent your own.</p><ul><li><strong>Ritual -</strong> The crew has undergone a ritual blending of blood, sharing of tattoos, or similar process which binds them together for good or for ill. This ritual allows the Crew to benefit from spells that would otherwise only affect one of them, though in exchange they are all affected by harmful spells that would target only a single creature.</li><li><strong>Deific Involvement -</strong> One of the deities has a particular love for teamwork, and smiles upon those who sacrifice their individual needs for the good of their fellows. Teams that train together, and act as one when facing their foes, receive this deity's boon, which creates a web of sympathetic magic between the members.</li><li><strong>Empathetic Resonance -</strong> The ties of sympathetic magic are not actually a conduit. Only a single creature might experience an effect, but either due to an empathetic response, or by disrupting the cohesion of the group, the aggregate effect on the group produces a result that matches what we might expect if it were cast on a single creature.</li></ul></div></details><details><summary class=\"exposition\"><h2 class=\"stylish-summary\">Usage</h2></summary><div style=\"width:90%;background-color:floralwhite;padding:10px 30px;margin-left:5%;margin-top:0px;border-radius:0px 0px 15px 15px\"><p>The Crew Template has been designed so that you can safely substitute any individual creature for a Crew of the same level with minimal impact on the balance of your game. If you are running a campaign where the majority of adversaries are humanoids, you may wish to increase the proportion of crews your party faces as they level up. Doing so will create a clear sense of progression as their opposition is forced to send larger numbers of foes to muster an adequate challenge to your party. This can be particularly effective if you apply the Crew template to foes your players have faced before. </p><p>If you desire, Crews could make up the majority of the opposition in your campaign without any undue impacts on your campaign balance. However, if you do choose to take that approach, you will want to ensure the majority of treasure comes either from bosses or story/achievement rewards. The equipment carried by crews will typically be well below your party's level. </p><p>There is of course no requirement that the Crew Template be applied only to humanoids; any creature that is between size Tiny and Large can be turned into a Crew of creatures using the templates in Step 1. This is especially useful at high levels when you may find that there are fewer premade NPCs available for use with the template. Fey and Outsiders are prime targets to turn into high level crews. </p><p>While Crews were designed to represent groups of your party's weaker foes, if your narrative supports it a Crew can be a satisfying boss encounter. Many of the Crew Abilities give the Crew better action economy, making for more dynamic encounters.</p></div></details><details><summary class=\"exposition\"><h2 class=\"stylish-summary\">Design Philosophy</h2></summary><div style=\"width:90%;background-color:floralwhite;padding:10px 30px;margin-left:5%;margin-top:0px;border-radius:0px 0px 15px 15px\"><p>Crews materialized as a means to counteract the \"Bandit in Ebony Armour\" issue that is observed in games with level-based scaling like Oblivion or Skyrim. In these games as the players level up the whole world levels up with them, which can undermine any feeling of progression, especially if your party are facing similar foes. Crews are designed to counteract that experience that by allowing you to easily throw a group of lower level adversaries against your players, while still providing a challenge appropriate to their level. By expanding the scale of their combats, it creates a sense of progression. This can be particularly effective if you apple the template to foes the party has faced before. </p><p>The obvious question is:\"Why invent Crews at all, why not simply use troops?\" The answer is multi-faceted, but primarily comes down to maintaining game balance.  If you were to replace a large proportion of the creatures your PCs faced with Paizo's troops, AC becomes largely meaningless and Reflex saves play a disproportionate role in determining the defensive capabilities of the party. Moreover, on the offensive side Troop Defences shift the balance of the game considerably towards the use of low level, repeatable area effect spells as a means to reliably trigger the troops weakness and bypass the damage thresholds, while making many single target spells virtually unusable. Finally, troops are difficult to use in play, their unique mechanics and the sheer number of individual tokens to be moved (should you choose to utilize the troop's capability to spread out) make running them a lot of extra work. Meaning that Troops are best saved for the occasional encounter and are not viable as the bread and butter of your campaign.</p><p>With that in mind Crews have been designed to minimize any changes to the overall balance of the game while still allowing your players to feel as though they are fighting a large group of enemies. To this end a minor weakness to area effect and splash damage has been included to preserve the feeling of area effect magic being especially effective against groups of foes, and crews can be targeted twice for abilities such as swipe allowing your martial character who have specialized into fighting multiple foes to feel effective and in their element when fighting Crews (Note: this is not meant to include cantrips like electric arc which do not need the help, which is why I have worded the ability as effects which require you to select two adjacent creatures, but at your discretion you might choose to allow abilities like ricochet shot, through shot, or even a spell like scorching ray to target the Crew a second time. I recommend erring on the side of caution should you choose to do so, if an ability interpreted as being able to work this way seems too good to be true it probably is). But otherwise the Crew acts exactly like a single creature would, meaning spells and effects that target a single creature function normally for the Crew.  This means that aside from a minor buff to abilities designed to fight groups of enemies, the fundamental balance of the various offensive abilities is preserved. On the defensive side, Crews have standard attacks which mostly target AC, with the occasional creature having spells or abilities that allow it to target saving throws, in line with most other creatures in the bestiaries, this maintains the balance of the various defenses a player might choose from. </p><p>Now Crews needed to be higher level than the base creature otherwise they don't serve the stated goals. I wanted the Crews to be of a reasonable size to fit on most battle maps, and settled on a group of 4 to 6 individuals. With the understanding that working closely together would allow the individuals to stand closer together, meaning they could safely occupy an area roughly equivalent to that taken up by 4 individual creatures of the same size.  One unfortunate side effect of this is that Crew's composed of huge or gargantuan creatures are not feasible due to their size, which is a real shame I love the idea of a Crew of giants. Thinking about 4 squares for medium creature sort of naturally led to considering a level adjustment of +4.  To determine the appropriate amount by which to boost the various abilities and stats for the Crew Template, the Creature Building tables from the Gamemastery Guide were used as a baseline and I looked at the average increase a creature would experience to their checks and DCs when going up 4 levels, and imitated that, with the boost being lower for low level creatures to match the slower progression in values for creatures level 4 and below.</p><p>Now when you're advancing a creature by 4 levels, raw increases to its statistics are insufficient to create a compelling creature, the creature should also have more powerful and intersting abilities. To that end I created the Crew Abilities listed in Step. These abilities were created with a mind towards developing abilities that reinforced the theme of a group of individuals working together to great effect. Like many of the other abilities included in Mercenary Market Volume 1. I've generally tried to err on the side of abilities that are more active in nature, with many of the passive abilities improving the capabilities of existing actions. The most involved of these abilities are those that relate to spellcasting.</p><p>For spellcasters a raw increase in stats is unlikely to create a satisfying or effective opponent, so an alternate means of advancement had to be considered. Three primary abilities that were created to boost the Crew's spellcasting capabilities while reinforcing the theme of a Crew of lower level mages working together, Joint Summoning, Simultaneous Casting and United Casting . Each of these abilities reinforces the Crew's capabilities in a different way. Joint Summoning plays on the fantasy of a group of summoners working together to call forth powerful creatures to do their bidding by providing the Crew with extra slots of high power specifically for summoning spells, of the three abilities it represents a much smaller increase in power, meaning it can be used alongside either united casting or simultaneous casting. United Casting takes the idea of many mages working together to produce greater effects by raising the level of the base creature's spell slots allowing it to upcast any of its existing low level spells. Finally, Simultaneous Casting provides the Crew with more weaker spells and allows it to simultaneously cast a cantrip along with one of its spells each turn, it balances out this power by not granting the Crew any new higher level spell slots meaning its spells will always be below the party's level. Given the large power increase represented by both United Casting and Simultaneous Casting the two cannot be used together on the same Crew. </p><p>The Crew Templates let you quickly create a wide variety of crews from existing NPCs. With the Crew Abilities you can even generate different crews from the same Base Creature by selecting different Crew Abilities, to represent a group made up of the same foes that have undergone different training.  <br /><br />The last sticking point was the lore - how do we justify this group of four to six people being treated by various spells and effects as a single creature. I've included a separate dropdown entry with my lore justifications, so such a critical detail isn't lost in these ramblings.<br /><br />Ultimately I'm quite satisfied with the final result, as it allows for a campaign where your players face down a primarily human opposition without needing to have their opposition continually levelling up with them, instead you can slowly sprinkle more elite fighters and lieutenants in while using crews for the bulks of the opposition's forces. Especially at low levels the existance of the Ragtag Crew, which provides a +2 level adjustment allows for a steady sense of progression. Hopefully you'll find it as satisfying in play as I do.</p></div></details></div>","markdown":""},"_id":"9gfeVJcuMhGzcjlY","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":600000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"name":"Example Crews","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"mmDemo-logo\"><img style=\"border:0\" src=\"modules/pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo/art/MM.png\" /></div><div class=\"main-box\"><h4 class=\"mimic-h1\">Example Crews</h4><hr /><p style=\"width:85%\">In this Demo, example crews for the Archer, Conjuror and Provocateur are available to give you an idea of how the crew template functions.</p><h2 class=\"stylish\" style=\"text-align:center\">Catalogue of NPC Crews</h2><table style=\"width:85%;border-style:hidden;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;color:#050e18\" border=\"0\"><tbody><tr class=\"crews\"><td class=\"crews\"><details open style=\"margin-left:0.5em;font-size:0.8em\"><summary><strong>Archer Crews by level</strong></summary><div style=\"text-align:left;margin-left:1.0em\"><p style=\"padd