</td><td style=\"height:19px;font-size:0.8em;color:#050e18\"><details style=\"text-align:left;margin-left:15%\"><summary><strong>Wizards by level</strong></summary><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.39WcoXLAVE19JUEa]{Mercenary Wizard [1-2]}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.NwJxTzZb7XwmbGRF]{Mercenary Wizard [3-4]}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.WkED36XGaWaLVB8s]{Mercenary Wizard [5-6]}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.uRBF4jYThQUI6YN7]{Mercenary Wizard [7-8]}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.Ela24uWRAQKJirxm]{Mercenary Wizard [9-10]}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.gZhtAmEnlqLC7U8l]{Mercenary Wizard [11-12]}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.5AvTCzq7towZNe61]{Mercenary Wizard [13-14]}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.iS0JaR9u47qsFKL3]{Mercenary Wizard [15-16]}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.R4kFk0cHffbdGhbw]{Mercenary Wizard [17-18]}</p></details></td></tr></tbody></table><div style=\"width:94%;margin:0 auto\"><details><summary class=\"exposition\"><h2 class=\"stylish-summary\">Usage</h2></summary><div style=\"width:90%;background-color:floralwhite;padding:10px 30px;margin-left:5%;margin-top:0px;border-radius:0px 0px 15px 15px\"><p>NPCs with class have been provided for use for levels between 1 and 18, allowing you to use them with minimal modification for the majority of any campaign.</p><p>Melee characters are listed with a range of three levels, for example [1-3]. The NPC is of the median level; however by applying either the Elite or Weak template, you can use those NPCs for the higher or lower level listed in the range. </p><p>Spellcasting characters are listed with a range of two levels, for example [1-2]. You'll find the actual NPC is the higher of the two levels. Given the increase in power and versatility that comes with learning a new level of spells, it is recommended that you do not use these NPCs with the Elite template, but they are readily compatible with the Weak template. Furthermore, given the adjustments applied by the Weak template to spell damage, I do not recommend adjusting the number of spell slots.</p><p>NPCs have been provided with a minimal amount of gear based on table 2-4: Safe Items from the Gamemastery Guide, focusing entirely on fundamental rune progression. While this means you can slot them into your game with a minimal impact on your party's treasure, if you are using them as the base for a significant foe you will want to expand upon and upgrade upon the gear provided, particularly in terms of consumables, worn or held magic items, and things like scrolls, staves and wands for spellcasting NPCs. Please note however, the NPC statistics already reflect appropriate values for creatures of their level, based on Paizo's creature creation guidelines, so if you are upgrading the fundamental runes (+x potency runes, resilience, striking) I would recommend exercising caution with changing those values, although applying the effects of property runes should be acceptable, especially if your players are level 5+. </p><p>These NPCs are designed to be most appropriate for use as named antagonists,  either directly unmodified or tweaked to match your needs. While NPCs with Class can be dropped into the world to represent generic antagonists of the appropriate player class, care should be taken to avoid the Skyrim bandit problem, where all the background NPCs level up with the party. If you are looking to challenge a high level party with generic underlings, either @UUID[Compendium.pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-journals.1s34nyLF4vYUxsHX.JournalEntryPage.J5arLCsj7pbrI1eQ]{Crews} or @UUID[Compendium.pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-journals.1s34nyLF4vYUxsHX.JournalEntryPage.LVylAkC1NWnXxLul]{Troops} may be more suitable while maintaining a stronger sense of progression. </p></div></details><details><summary class=\"exposition\"><h2 class=\"stylish-summary\">Design Philosophy</h2></summary><div style=\"width:90%;background-color:floralwhite;padding:10px 30px;margin-left:5%;margin-top:0px;border-radius:0px 0px 15px 15px\"><p>These NPCs have been designed to emulate player classes, although in many cases abilities have been simplified, condensed or reflavoured to make the NPCs easier to run for GMs. To appropriately capture the flavour of their respective classes, these NPCs with Class tend to have more abilities, than the other NPCs included in Mercenary Market Volume 1, making them more complex to run. These design choices make NPCs with class most appropriate for use as named antagonists. Although, these NPCs will still tend to have fewer  abilities than a PC of the same level, and no attempt has been made to include skill feats or ancestry feats, instead trading that versatility for the slight increase in raw power that is intrinsic to Paizo's creature building guidelines.</p><p>While we have attempted to capture the essence and flavour of each class, we have not restricted ourselves to the abilities and feats described in the core rulebook, some custom abilities have been created. While these new abilities have not been written up as player facing feats, they could be adapted for uncommon or rare player options. Although, if adapted without any tweaking, they will tend to be slightly more powerful than standard player options of the same level, as NPCs tend have fewer, slightly more powerful abilities, to make up for their lack of versatility and to make them easier to run.</p><p>Generally an attempt has been made to remove or modify abilities that are likely to be frustrating for players. For example, many classes get abilities to upgrade successes on saves to critical successes for their highest save, which given the relatively high saves of NPCs can be very frustrating for spellcasting PCs. To counteract this, we have omitted many of these abilities, except in cases were we felt these abilities were essential to the flavour of the class, such as Evasion on the Rogue.</p><p>The progression of these characters is modelled after that of their respective classes, with slight deviations as appropriate.</p></div></details></div></div>","markdown":""},"_id":"JWFJTzMI86q256tm","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":1100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"name":"NPCs with Jobs","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"mmDemo-logo\"><img style=\"border:0\" src=\"modules/pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo/art/MM.png\" /></div><div class=\"main-box\"><h4 class=\"mimic-h1\">NPCs with Jobs</h4><hr /><p style=\"width:85%\">Here you'll find a catalogue of NPCs built to fill a particular combat role or job.  In volume 1, each role is represented by several NPCs. Multiple versions of different levels exist for each NPC. </p><p style=\"width:85%\">In this demo only the Doctor, Guardian and Necromancer are available, all the other detail dropdowns are empty.</p><h2 class=\"plain\">Catalogue of NPCs by Combat Role</h2><hr /><table style=\"margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;width:90%;border-style:hidden\" border=\"0\"><tbody><tr style=\"height:19px\"><td style=\"width:33%;text-align:center;background-color:#050e18;font-size:0.9em;height:19px\"><strong>Artillery</strong></td><td style=\"width:33%;text-align:center;background-color:#050e18;font-size:0.9em;height:19px\"><strong>Bruiser</strong></td><td style=\"width:33%;text-align:center;background-color:#050e18;font-size:0.9em;height:19px\"><strong>Defender</st