15%\"><summary><strong>Conjurors by level</strong></summary></details><details open style=\"text-align:left;margin-left:15%\"><summary><strong>Doctors by level</strong></summary><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.vK7mfMwQxtEx9P65]{Doctor [1-3]}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.f9AGp30o7RJ9yB2I]{Doctor [4-6]}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.VLbdDtELpaovYUmw]{Doctor [7-9]}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.cRLtEbs4aQIYVn7m]{Doctor [10-12]}</p></details><details style=\"text-align:left;margin-left:15%\"><summary><strong>Wrestlers by level</strong></summary></details></td><td style=\"height:19px;font-size:0.8em;color:#050e18\"><details style=\"text-align:left;margin-left:15%\"><summary><strong>Conjurors by level</strong></summary></details><details open style=\"text-align:left;margin-left:15%\"><summary><strong>Necromancers by level</strong></summary><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.db8QSYD85JOaNq1J]{Necromancer [1-2]}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.WuUwrRyVFNKSSWrJ]{Necromancer [3-4]}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.Cm7R4YLW566QC4i3]{Necromancer [5-6]}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.0XReUhUQAqQqvRfi]{Necromancer [7-8]}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.Fq4ZYL84OMOyO6gI]{Necromancer [9-10]}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.e4cLTdpyfZpZ5Tsl]{Necromancer [11-12]}</p></details><details style=\"text-align:left;margin-left:15%\"><summary><strong>Tacticians by level</strong></summary></details></td><td style=\"height:19px;font-size:0.8em;color:#050e18\"><details style=\"text-align:left;margin-left:15%\"><summary><strong>Doctors by level</strong></summary><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.vK7mfMwQxtEx9P65]{Doctor [1-3]}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.f9AGp30o7RJ9yB2I]{Doctor [4-6]}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.VLbdDtELpaovYUmw]{Doctor [7-9]}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.cRLtEbs4aQIYVn7m]{Doctor [10-12]}</p></details><details style=\"text-align:left;margin-left:15%\"><summary><strong>Priestesses by level</strong></summary></details></td></tr><tr style=\"height:19px\"><td style=\"width:33%;text-align:center;background-color:#050e18;font-size:0.9em;height:19px\"><strong>Skirmisher</strong></td><td style=\"width:33%;text-align:center;background-color:#050e18;font-size:0.9em;height:19px\"><strong>Good against Single-Targets</strong></td><td style=\"width:33%;text-align:center;background-color:#050e18;font-size:0.9em;height:19px\"><strong>Good Against Multiple-Targets</strong></td></tr><tr style=\"height:19px;vertical-align:top\"><td style=\"height:19px;font-size:0.8em;color:#050e18\"><details style=\"text-align:left;margin-left:15%\"><summary><strong>Cutpurses by level</strong></summary></details><details style=\"text-align:left;margin-left:15%\"><summary><strong>Doctors by level</strong></summary><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.vK7mfMwQxtEx9P65]{Doctor [1-3]}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.f9AGp30o7RJ9yB2I]{Doctor [4-6]}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.VLbdDtELpaovYUmw]{Doctor [7-9]}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.cRLtEbs4aQIYVn7m]{Doctor [10-12]}</p></details><details style=\"text-align:left;margin-left:15%\"><summary><strong>Runic Warriors by level</strong></summary></details></td><td style=\"height:19px;font-size:0.8em;color:#050e18\"><details style=\"text-align:left;margin-left:15%\"><summary><strong>Archers by level</strong></summary></details><details style=\"text-align:left;margin-left:15%\"><summary><strong>Cutpurses by level</strong></summary></details><details style=\"text-align:left;margin-left:15%\"><summary><strong>Doctors by level</strong></summary><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.vK7mfMwQxtEx9P65]{Doctor [1-3]}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.f9AGp30o7RJ9yB2I]{Doctor [4-6]}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.VLbdDtELpaovYUmw]{Doctor [7-9]}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.cRLtEbs4aQIYVn7m]{Doctor [10-12]}</p></details><details style=\"text-align:left;margin-left:15%\"><summary><strong>Enforcers by level</strong></summary></details><details style=\"text-align:left;margin-left:15%\"><summary><strong>Provocateurs by level</strong></summary></details><details style=\"text-align:left;margin-left:15%\"><summary><strong>Runic Warriors by level</strong></summary></details><details style=\"text-align:left;margin-left:15%\"><summary><strong>Wrestlers by level</strong></summary></details></td><td style=\"height:19px;font-size:0.8em;color:#050e18\"><details style=\"text-align:left;margin-left:15%\"><summary><strong>Conjurors by level</strong></summary></details><details style=\"text-align:left;margin-left:15%\"><summary><strong>Guardians by level</strong></summary><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.lpnw05ash7Ta0u6T]{Guardian [1-3]}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.mLBjsTBo94iK8GXP]{Guardian [4-6]}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.LYFqsURmfnpHXzMA]{Guardian [7-9]}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.sH9NvA3CQAxBaIMp]{Guardian [10-12]}</p></details><details style=\"text-align:left;margin-left:15%\"><summary><strong>Hydromancers by level</strong></summary></details><details style=\"text-align:left;margin-left:15%\"><summary><strong>Priestesses by level</strong></summary></details><details style=\"text-align:left;margin-left:15%\"><summary><strong>Ravagers by level</strong></summary></details></td></tr></tbody></table><div style=\"width:92%;margin:0 auto\"><details><summary class=\"exposition\"><h2 class=\"stylish-summary\">Usage</h2></summary><div style=\"width:90%;background-color:floralwhite;padding:10px 30px;margin-left:5%;margin-top:0px;border-radius:0px 0px 15px 15px\"><p>Some NPCs can fill multiple roles and will appear on the table in several locations. </p><p>Melee characters are listed with a range of three levels, for example [1-3]. The NPC is of the median level; however by applying either the Elite or Weak template, you can use those NPCs for the higher or lower level listed in the range. </p><p style=\"margin-top:var(--p-space,1em)\">Spellcasting characters are listed with a range of two levels, for example [1-2]. You'll find the actual NPC is the higher of the two levels. Given the increase in power and versatility that comes with learning a new level of spells, it is recommended that you do not use these NPCs with the Elite template, but they are readily compatible with the Weak template. Furthermore, given the adjustments applied by the Weak template to spell damage, I do not recommend adjusting the number of spell slots.</p><p style=\"margin-top:var(--p-space,1em)\">NPCs have been provided with a minimal amount of gear based on table 2-4: Safe Items from the Gamemastery Guide, focusing entirely on fundamental rune progression. While this means you can slot them into your game with a minimal impact on your party's treasure, if you are using them as the base for a significant foe you will want to expand upon or upgrade upon the gear provided, particularly in terms of consumables, worn or held magic items, and things like scrolls, staves and wands for spellcasting NPCs. The NPC statistics already reflect appropriate values for creatures of their level based on Paizo's creature creation guidelines, so if you are upgrading the fundamental rules (+x potency rules, resilience, striking) I would recommend exercising caution with changing those values, although applying the effects of property runes should be acceptable, especially if your players are level 5+. </p><p style=\"margin-top:var(--p-space,1em)\">These NPCs are designed to have lower complexity than the NPCs with Classes and are particularly appropriate for use as supporting characters. For major named antagonists it may be beneficial to select one to two feats from an appropriate class, ancestry or skill to expand upon their versatility and make for a more complex villain. </p><p style=\"margin-top:var(--p-space,1em)\">For higher level threats, the intention is that individual NPCs of this sort stop being a threat to the party, and you need to transition to using @UUID[Compendium.pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-journals.1s34nyLF4vYUxsHX.JournalEntryPage.J5arLCsj7pbrI1eQ]{Crews}. I've intentionally not created any NPCs with jobs over level 12 to explicitly encourage this transition.</p></div></details><details><summary class=\"exposition\"><h2 class=\"stylish-summary\">Design Philosophy</h2></summary><div style=\"width:90%;background-color:floralwhite;padding:10px 30px;margin-left:5%;margin-top:0px;border-radius:0px 0px 15px 15px\"><p>In making these NPCs I have split them into seven different combat roles. Each NPC was designed to fulfill one or more of these combat roles, while remaining true to the core identity of whatever job that NPC has. Thus, abilities have been designed such that the Tactician has abilities that feel appropriate for someone who makes their living as a tactician, while the Necromancer has abilities that feel appropriate for someone who raises the dead, even through both act as leaders. In comparison to the NPCs with Class, NPCs with Jobs have been generally designed to have fewer and simpler abilities to make them easier to run; and while these NPCs can make for great named antagonists they tend to be simpler in design making them especially suitable for use as lackeys.</p><p>Many of these NPCs have brand new abilities that are particularly suited to their theme, these abilities will tend to be more powerful than a player's ability of the same level to compensate for the relative lack of breadth these NPCs have compared to player characters. However, with some tweaking, an ambitious GM could turn these unique mechanics and the progression demonstrated between the lower and high level NPCs with jobs into player facing archetypes. In general, many of these abilities are intended to be player visible. What I mean by that is, they should be discoverable with recall knowledge, and that the abilities have been designed to be things the NPCs actively do, rather than passive bonuses. Where passive bonuses do exist I've endeavored to make them significant enough and obvious enough based on the concept that I hope your players will be able to guess to avoid a particular tactic or save based on what sort of NPC they are facing. </p><p>I've only included NPCs with levels between 1 to 12 in this collection, with the notion that based on what Paizo has created, level 1 to 12 is a believable level of power for these more generic NPCs, and they could be feasible slotted into your adventure paths and Golarion games without breaking versamillatude. As your party moves into the mid to high levels individual NPCs give way to crews of NPCs to appropriately challenge your players, while creating a sense of realistic scaling in the scope and stakes of what your PCs are able to accomplish. With the Crew Templates these foes can thus remains viable threats up until the final few levels of your campaigns.</p></div></details></div></div>","markdown":""},"_id":"m3ez8MLOFi0NWUSH","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":1250000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"name":"Troops","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"mmDemo-logo\"><img style=\"border:0\" src=\"modules/pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo/art/MM.png\" /></div><div class=\"main-box\"><h4 class=\"mimic-h1\">Troops</h4><hr /><p style=\"width:85%\">Here you'll find a catalogue of all the new troops included in Mercenary Marketplace Volume 1. In volume 1, troops have been produced for levels between 4 and 18. The demo contains 4 troops for you to use.</p><h2 class=\"plain\">Catalogue of Troops by Level</h2><hr /><table style=\"width:85%;border-style:hidden;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto\" border=\"0\"><tbody><tr style=\"height:19px\"><td style=\"width:12.5504%;background-color:#050e18;font-size:0.9em;height:19px\"><strong>Level</strong></td><td style=\"width:87.4067%;background-color:#050e18;font-size:0.9em;height:19px\"><strong>Troops</strong></td></tr><tr style=\"height:19px\"><td style=\"width:12.5504%;height:19px;font-size:0.8em;background-color:#cfc5af;color:#050e18\"><strong>4</strong></td><td style=\"width:87.4067%;height:19px;font-size:0.8em;background-color:#cfc5af;color:#050e18\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.UgGzOfg3Sb53c4yX]{Goblin Raiders [4]}, Unenthusiastic Militia</td></tr><tr style=\"height:19px\"><td style=\"width:12.5504%;height:19px;font-size:0.8em;background-color:#e3ddcf;color:#050e18\"><strong>5</strong></td><td style=\"width:87.4067%;height:19px;font-size:0.8em;background-color:#e3ddcf;color:#050e18\">Angry Mob, @Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.LH3TX2hHy71ce2Mm]{Beleaguered Mercenary Company [5]}</td></tr><tr style=\"height:19px\"><td style=\"width:12.5504%;height:19px;font-size:0.8em;background-color:#cfc5af;color:#050e18\"><strong>6</strong></td><td style=\"width:87.4067%;height:19px;font-size:0.8em;background-color:#cfc5af;color:#050e18\">Hunting Party, Spear Infantry</td></tr><tr style=\"height:19px\"><td style=\"width:12.5504%;height:19px;font-size:0.8em;background-color:#e3ddcf;color:#050e18\"><strong>7</strong></td><td style=\"width:87.4067%;height:19px;font-size:0.8em;background-color:#e3ddcf;color:#050e18\">Archer Battalion, Cavalry Cohort</td></tr><tr style=\"height:19px\"><td style=\"width:12.5504%;height:19px;font-size:0.8em;background-color:#cfc5af;color:#050e18\"><strong>8</strong></td><td style=\"width:87.4067%;height:19px;font-size:0.8em;background-color:#cfc5af;color:#050e18\">Armoured Infantry, Untested Warmage Circle</td></tr><tr style=\"height:19px\"><td style=\"width:12.5504%;height:19px;font-size:0.8em;background-color:#e3ddcf;color:#050e18\"><strong>9</strong></td><td style=\"width:87.4067%;height:19px;font-size:0.8em;background-color:#e3ddcf;color:#050e18\">Drake Slayers, Druidic Circle</td></tr><tr style=\"height:19px\"><td style=\"width:12.5504%;height:19px;font-size:0.8em;background-color:#cfc5af;color:#050e18\"><strong>10</strong></td><td style=\"width:87.4067%;height:19px;font-size:0.8em;background-color:#cfc5af;color:#050e18\">Fervent Faithful, Northern Raiding Party</td></tr><tr style=\"height:19px\"><td style=\"width:12.5504%;height:19px;font-size:0.8em;background-color:#e3ddcf;color:#050e18\"><strong>11</strong></td><td style=\"width:87.4067%;height:19px;font-size:0.8em;background-color:#e3ddcf;color:#050e18\">Bloodthirsty Mob, Hardened Spear Infantry</td></tr><tr style=\"height:19px\"><td style=\"width:12.5504%;height:19px;font-size:0.8em;background-color:#cfc5af;color:#050e18\"><strong>12</strong></td><td style=\"width:87.4067%;height:19px;font-size:0.8em;background-color:#cfc5af;color:#050e18\">Mercenary Company, Sappers</td></tr><tr style=\"height:19px\"><td style=\"width:12.5504%;height:19px;font-size:0.8em;background-color:#e3ddcf;color:#050e18\"><strong>13</strong></td><td style=\"width:87.4067%;height:19px;font-size:0.8em;background-color:#e3ddcf;color:#050e18\">Decorated Archer Battalion, Demonic Cultists</td></tr><tr style=\"height:19px\"><td style=\"width:12.5504%;height:19px;font-size:0.8em;background-color:#cfc5af;color:#050e18\"><strong>14</strong></td><td style=\"width:87.4067%;height:19px;font-size:0.8em;background-color:#cfc5af;color:#050e18\">Decorated Cavalry Cohort, @Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.sRTSD4oxm20EBWnd]{Royal Guard [14]}</td></tr><tr style=\"height:19px\"><td style=\"width:12.5504%;height:19px;font-size:0.8em;background-color:#e3ddcf;color:#050e18\"><strong>15</strong></td><td style=\"width:87.4067%;height:19px;font-size:0.8em;background-color:#e3ddcf;color:#050e18\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-actors.T54v9SD1BNCmcHKx]{Mad Mutagenists [15]}</td></tr><tr style=\"height:19px\"><td style=\"width:12.5504%;height:19px;font-size:0.8em;background-color:#cfc5af;color:#050e18\"><strong>16</strong></td><td style=\"width:87.4067%;height:19px;font-size:0.8em;background-color:#cfc5af;color:#050e18\">Thane's Raiding Party</td></tr><tr style=\"height:19px\"><td style=\"width:12.5504%;height:19px;font-size:0.8em;background-color:#e3ddcf;color:#050e18\"><strong>17</strong></td><td style=\"width:87.4067%;height:19px;font-size:0.8em;background-color:#e3ddcf;color:#050e18\">Enlightened Disciples</td></tr><tr style=\"height:19px\"><td style=\"width:12.5504%;height:19px;font-size:0.8em;background-color:#cfc5af;color:#050e18\"><strong>18</strong></td><td style=\"width:87.4067%;height:19px;font-size:0.8em;background-color:#cfc5af;color:#050e18\">Imperial Crown Guard</td></tr></tbody></table><div style=\"width:90%;margin:0 auto\"><details><summary class=\"exposition\"><h2 class=\"stylish-summary\">Usage</h2></summary><div style=\"width:90%;background-color:floralwhite;padding:10px 30px;margin-left:5%;margin-top:0px;border-radius:0px 0px 15px 15px\"><p>Given the limitations of FoundryVTT at present, templates like Weak and Elite do not affect inline damage rolls. Given that inline rolls are the primary sort of damage roll used for troops, each troop is presented at a single level only rather than a level range. I don't recommend trying to modify your troops with the Weak and Elite adjustments unless you're prepared to make a number of manual adjustments.</p><p>Troops have been presented as Gargantuan creatures to reflect the rules, however, if you wish to have troops that can alter their shape per the rules in Form Up, you will wish to adjust the size to medium and place 16 medium tokens all linked to the initial imported actor. This set up allows you to freely move the individual members around while still providing a single shared health bar. If you not wish to take this approach and would instead prefer to treat the troop as a gargantuan creature, then you will likely want to treat the troops level as one level lower, especially in the case of troops that predominately deal melee damage. The inability to alter the shape of the troop will have a strongly detrimental impact of the troop's damage output, as it will be unable to shift around to catch most of the party with its attacks. For troops that mostly rely on ranged damage or spellcasting, this adjustment is unnecessary. </p></div></details><details><summary class=\"exposition\"><h2 class=\"stylish-summary\">Troop Creation Guidelines</h2></summary><div style=\"width:90%;background-color:floralwhite;padding:10px 30px;margin-left:5%;margin-top:0px;border-radius:0px 0px 15px 15px\"><p>The Full version of Mercenary Marketplace contains guidelines for creating your own troops.</p></div></details><details><summary class=\"exposition\"><h2 class=\"stylish-summary\">Design Philosophy</h2></summary><div style=\"width:90%;background-color:floralwhite;padding:10px 30px;margin-left:5%;margin-top:0px;border-radius:0px 0px 15px 15px\"><p>I find the weakness of Paizo's troops to Area Effect spells to be very unsatisfying, the weakness has the same effect whether you spend a first level burning hands spell or a 10th level meteor swarm. Whereas I feel that a higher level area effect spell used on a troop should produce a proportionately greater effect. My solution to address this grip was is to replace the weakness with a Area Effect Vulnerability, which decreases the degree of success for troops against area effect spells, thus making their effectiveness naturally scale with the power of the spell. If you find you'd prefer the standard troop weaknesses, remove the Troop Area Effect Vulnerability and give the troop a weakness with a value equal to double its listed weakness to splash damage.</p><p>Wherever possible I've chosen to create abilities for these troops that reflect the fantasy evoked by the troop's name. Though, like all other actors included in Mercenary Marketplace Volume 1, I have not provided an explicit lore entry, as they are intended to be adapted to your world.</p></div></details></div></div>","markdown":""},"_id":"LVylAkC1NWnXxLul","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":1600000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}}],"name":"Mercenary Marketplace Demo Journals","ownership":{"default":0,"bfgnTwSJe6w6fxpV":3},"flags":{"pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo":{"ismmDemo":true},"core":{"viewMode":1,"sourceId":"JournalEntry.8DcD4RyopUR4Zagd"}},"_stats":{"systemId":"pf2e","systemVersion":"4.6.7","coreVersion":"10.291","createdTime":1662562755593,"modifiedTime":1673975682696,"lastModifiedBy":"bfgnTwSJe6w6fxpV"},"folder":null,"sort":0,"_id":"1s34nyLF4vYUxsHX"}
{"pages":[{"name":"Ancestry Templates","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"mmDemo-logo\"><img style=\"border:0\" src=\"modules/pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo/art/MM.png\" /></div><div class=\"main-box\"><h4 class=\"mimic-h1\">Ancestry Templates</h4><hr /><p style=\"width:90%;margin:0 auto\">Here you'll find a collection of templates that allow you to alter the ancestries of your NPCs. In the demo I've included ancestry templates for Dwarves, and Elves. In the full version of Mercenary Marketplace Volume 1, you'll find templates for the six common ancestries from the Pathfinder Second Edition Core Rulebook: Dwarves, Elves, Gnomes, Goblins, Halflings, and Humans. Additionally to celebrate the announcement of the ORC license Orc ancestry templates are also available.</p><h2 class=\"stylish\">Stepwise Instructions</h2><div style=\"width:90%;margin:0 auto\"><h3 class=\"dark\">Step 1. Select Ancestry</h3><p style=\"margin:0;padding:0\">Select an Ancestry Template. There are two types of Ancestry Template provided:</p><p><strong>Ability Boost Templates</strong> will provide the NPC with the base features of the ancestry (darkvision, speed, ancestry HP, etc.), benefits or penalties based on the Ability Boosts granted by that ancestry, and prompt you to select a heritage for that ancestry from those listed in Step 2.</p><p style=\"margin-left:2em\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-templates.yy7t29NuTsHteB8I]{Ancestry, Dwarf (Ability Boosts)} @Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-templates.ybW6A5BAywolnzJr]{Ancestry, Elf (Ability Boosts)} Ancestry, Gnome (Ability Boosts), Ancestry, Goblin (Ability Boosts), Ancestry, Halfling (Ability Boosts), Ancestry, Human (Ability Boosts), Ancestry, Orc (Ability Boosts)</p><p>      <strong>Heritage Only Templates</strong> will provide only the base features of the ancestry (darkvision, speed, ancestry HP), and prompt you to select a heritage for that ancestry from those listed in Step 2.</p><p style=\"margin-left:2em;padding-after:1em\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-templates.Nu01ejqWcdDb14oW]{Ancestry, Dwarf (Heritage Only)} @Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-templates.DN5k4nQb6XUCeuCd]{Ancestry, Elf (Heritage Only)} Ancestry, Gnome (Heritage Only), Ancestry, Goblin (Heritage Only), Ancestry, Halfling (Heritage Only), Ancestry, Human (Heritage Only), Ancestry, Orc (Heritage Only)</p><h3 class=\"dark\">Step 2. Select Heritage</h3><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">Select a heritage from the table below that matches your chosen ancestry.</p></div><table style=\"width:85.1095%;border-style:hidden;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;margin-top:0\" border=\"0\"><tbody><tr style=\"height:19px\"><td style=\"width:100%;text-align:center;background-color:#050e18;height:19px\"><strong>Dwarven Heritages</strong></td></tr><tr style=\"height:50px\"><td style=\"width:100%;text-align:center\"><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-abilities.HNmaqg4cO6XX0YTm]{Dwarf, Ancient-Blooded}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-abilities.Q3GKbJJlZWumMFxP]{Dwarf, Death Warden}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-abilities.0fbypbxrYP7yDH3G]{Dwarf, Forge Keeper}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-abilities.2RwlLZ35HZV2iKbk]{Dwarf, Stonefooted}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-abilities.46oGMaw2wAMr6r4p]{Dwarf, Strong-Blooded}</p></td></tr><tr style=\"height:19px\"><td style=\"width:100%;text-align:center;background-color:#050e18;height:19px\"><strong>Elven Heritages</strong></td></tr><tr style=\"height:50px\"><td style=\"width:100%;text-align:center;color:#050e18\"><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-abilities.p4PUQ8cvyY3Qz9LM]{Elf, Arctic}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-abilities.l0teXFHgmKoYbP0z]{Elf, Cavern}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-abilities.mywTHWd280hMTRNG]{Elf, Desert}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-abilities.G2DiKLuUrOQ8ifUN]{Elf, Seer}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-abilities.oOzGML8Blj2sjPrr]{Elf, Whisper}</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">@Compendium[pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo.mmDemo-abilities.QXoJvXtAPRrpXV3W]{Elf, Woodland}</p></td></tr><tr style=\"height:19px\"><td style=\"width:100%;text-align:center;background-color:#050e18;height:19px\"><strong>Gnomish Heritages</strong></td></tr><tr style=\"height:50px\"><td style=\"width:100%;text-align:center;color:#050e18\"><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">Gnome, Chameleon</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">Gnome, Fey-Touched</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">Gnome, Sensate</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">Gnome, Umbral</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">Gnome, Wellspring</p></td></tr><tr style=\"height:19px\"><td style=\"width:100%;text-align:center;background-color:#050e18;height:19px\"><strong>Goblin Heritages</strong></td></tr><tr style=\"height:50px\"><td style=\"width:100%;text-align:center;color:#050e18\"><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">Goblin, Charhide</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">Goblin, Hordefodder</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">Goblin, Irongut</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">Goblin, Snow</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">Goblin, Unbreakable</p></td></tr><tr style=\"height:19px\"><td style=\"width:100%;text-align:center;background-color:#050e18;height:19px\"><strong>Halfling Heritages</strong></td></tr><tr style=\"height:50px\"><td style=\"width:100%;text-align:center;color:#050e18\"><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">Halfling, Gutsy</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">Halfling, Lucky</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">Halfling, Shadowy</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">Halfling, Twilight</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">Halfling, Wildwood</p></td></tr><tr style=\"height:19px\"><td style=\"width:100%;text-align:center;background-color:#050e18;height:19px\"><strong>Human Heritages</strong></td></tr><tr style=\"height:50px\"><td style=\"width:100%;text-align:center;color:#050e18\"><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">Human, Half-Elf</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">Human, Half-Orc</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">Human, Skilled</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">Human, Versatile</p></td></tr><tr style=\"height:19px\"><td style=\"width:100%;text-align:center;background-color:#050e18;height:19px\"><strong>Orc Heritages</strong></td></tr><tr style=\"height:50px\"><td style=\"width:100%;text-align:center;color:#050e18\"><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">Orc, Badlands</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">Orc, Deep</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">Orc, Hold-Scarred</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">Orc, Rainfall</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\">Orc, Tusked</p></td></tr></tbody></table><div style=\"width:95%;padding:10px 30px;margin-left:3.5%;margin-top:0px;border-radius:0px 0px 15px 15px\"><h3 class=\"dark\">Step 3. Apply Template</h3><p>Apply your selected Ancestry Template from Step 1 by dragging it to the NPC token or character sheet of your choice. After you have dropped it on the token or sheet, a prompt will pop up asking which heritage you would like to apply to your NPC. The prompt will present a dropdown with the list of included heritages for that ancestry. If you are applying the Ancestry, Human (Ability Boost) template, it will first ask which ability boost you wish to apply, and then prompt you to select a heritage. The Ancestry Template will automatically apply the appropriate bonuses and penalties and, using the grant item rule element, add the selected heritage to your NPC.</p><h3 class=\"dark\">Step 4. Manual Adjustments</h3><p>Many of the ancestries have small adjustments that could not be automated. For most NPCs, you will need to manually adjust the languages known to include those granted by their ancestry. If the ancestry or heritage you have selected increases the NPC's maximum HP, then you will also need to manually update their current HP to match. You will want to apply any other manual adjustments listed on your chosen ancestry or heritage during this step. If the NPC you have applied the template to had a pre-existing ancestry trait that was not human, you will need to remove that manually.</p><h3 class=\"dark\">Step 5. Customize (Optional)</h3><p>These templates are designed to allow you to quickly adjust individual creatures to make them feel like they belong to a specific ancestry without adding a lot of complexity. If you are creating an NPC for whom you wish their ancestry to be an important element of their character, and you would like that to be reflected in their mechanics, you might consider adding an ancestry feat or two. Items of the feat type cannot be added to NPCs so you will need to convert the feat to an action with an appropriate action cost, using passive actions to represent feats with no action cost.</p></div><details><summary class=\"exposition\"><h2 class=\"stylish-summary\">Usage</h2></summary><div style=\"width:90%;background-color:floralwhite;padding:10px 30px;margin-left:5%;margin-top:0px;border-radius:0px 0px 15px 15px\"><p>As mentioned above, there are two types of Ancestry Templates, Ability Boost Templates and Heritage Only Templates. The former include benefits based on the standard ability score boosts for each ancestry, while the latter do not. Neither of the templates is completely balance neutral. An NPC with an Ancestry Template will be slightly more powerful or flexible than an NPC without one. Generally, I recommend using the included Ancestry Templates when you would like an NPC's ancestry and heritage to be reflected mechanically in their character, with the choice between Ability Boost and Heritage Only Templates being a choice about the level of mechanical impact you want the character's heritage and ancestry to have.</p><p>If you want to design an NPC whose ancestry is more central to their character or backstory, adding 1-2 converted ancestry feats of an appropriate level, as mentioned in Step 5,  is an excellent way to reinforce the theme of that character. </p><p>If you would like a mechanically lighter option, for NPCs where their ancestry is of less importance, I suggest taking a look at the ancestry adjustments included in the \"Using the NPC Gallery\" section in Chapter 5 of the Gamemastery Guide, or applying one of the Heritage Only Templates and choosing not to select a heritage. </p></div></details><details><summary class=\"exposition\"><h2 class=\"stylish-summary\">Design Philosophy</h2></summary><div style=\"width:90%;background-color:floralwhite;padding:10px 30px;margin-left:5%;margin-top:0px;border-radius:0px 0px 15px 15px\"><p>The Ancestry Templates were designed to be usable with the various NPCs included in Mercenary Market Volume 1, and with those published by Paizo. I had made the assumption that the NPC you are applying any Ancestry Template to is human, consequently, the template will automatically remove the human trait if it is present, but any other pre-existing ancestry traits that the NPC has are not removed. While human is the assumed baseline, if the NPC you are applying the template to is of a size different than medium, it will still be adjusted to the appropriate size for the Ancestry Template you have selected.</p><p>The primary design goal in creating the Ancestry Templates was to create something that captured the core feeling of the various ancestries, while not having a dramatic impact on game balance. For me, a key part of capturing the feeling of the various ancestries was to reflect the ancestry ability boosts in the final result, such that a player could correctly infer that a dwarf would be hardier than average, while an elf or halfling would be more nimble.</p><p>A straight increase to the ability scores proved imbalanced, as even with offsetting penalties to counteract its effects it produced NPCs that were notably more effective if they happened to have one of the ability boost scores as a key ability, and notably less effective if they did not. To counteract these issues, I developed a set of benefits/penalties that could be granted for each ability that were relatively in line with one another in terms of the benefits they granted, while also feeling appropriate to the mechanics of the game. The final result is somewhat imperfect,  the six scores are not perfectly balanced with each other, and the effects are not entirely restricted to matching the benefits a player character would recieve for each ability boost. However, these benefits produce results results that are mechanically sound while being interesting and recognizable for your players. </p><div style=\"margin-left:2em\"><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\"><strong>Strength </strong>(+1 to Strike Damage (with Melee, Thrown, and Propulsive Strikes) and Athletics).</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\"><strong>Dexterity </strong>(+1 to Reflex Saves, Acrobatics, Stealth, and Thievery).</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\"><strong>Constitution </strong>(+1 to Fortitude Saves, and +1 HP per level)</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\"><strong>Intelligence </strong>(+1 to Skill Checks)</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\"><strong>Wisdom </strong>(+1 to Will Saves, Perception, Medicine, Nature, Religion, and Survival)</p><p style=\"padding:0;margin:0\"><strong>Charisma </strong>(+1 to Spell Damage and Deception, Diplomacy, Intimidation, and Performance)</p></div><p>Strength was in many ways one of the easiest to design. Athletics is a fairly potent skill that many creatures possess, and virtually all creatures have an option to deal some form of strike damage. And both of these these benefits/penalties have a relatively small impact compared to altering the NPCs strength-based attack rolls. </p><p>Dexterity was much harder to design, and it ended up slightly more potent that Strength. stripping out benefits to AC, and dexterity-based attack rolls from the benefits was a clear choice, but ultimately I decided a benefit to Reflex saves could stay. While a boost to Reflex saves is more likely to have a gameplay impact than +1 to damage, most spellcasters will have the ability to choose which save they target. Being able to look at a halfling, elf, or goblin as a player and go, oh, that NPC is going to be harder to hit with abilities that target Reflex feels good as it reinforces a sense of verisimilitude. And finally, I already knew I wanted to include a boost to Fortitude saves for Constitution, and including a save boost for Con and not Dex felt like it would undermine my attempts at creating verisimilitude. Including boosts of the various Dexterity keyed skills felt like an important thing to include for many of the same reasons. </p><p>Constitution was also fairly easy, a small increase to HP of 1 per level and Fortitude saves felt like pretty much the baseline power level of the benefits I wanted an ability boost to grant. The only wrinkle was making sure that a Constitution boost on a level -1 NPC or a level 0 NPC didn't have a counterintuitive effect, to prevent that from occurring the level used to calculate the HP increase was set to a minimum value of 1. </p><p>Intelligence was the black sheep of the family, while many of its skills are exceptionally useful for recalling knowledge it is fairly rare for NPCs to make recall knowledge checks in my experience, and granting additional trained skills was difficult to automate without being cumbersome. The compromise I reached was to have it increase all skills by 1, to reflect the opportunity a more intelligent creature would have to increase a broad variety of skills. Given that most NPCs have a handful of skills they use regularly while being untrained in the majority of skills the scope of this benefit is in many ways restrained to the skills each creature uses regularly, which falls roughly in line with the level of power I wanted these ability boosts to have. DCs for spells and effects were excluded for much the same reasons that Str and Dex boosts did not affect attack rolls. </p><p>Wisdom is another ability that ended up more potent than I would like, for the same reasons discussed with Dexterity I wanted to include Will saves in the ability boost benefits. And with Perception being both a useful attribute in general for countering PC stealth checks, while also being the most common determinant of initiative rolls it is also a potent benefit. On the plus side, the Wisdom skills of Medicine, Religion, Nature, and Survival, while useful, tend to be less commonly used by NPCs, which helps keep Wisdom from being the unparalleled star of the show, instead it ends up slightly better than average like Dex.</p><p>Charisma was in a similar boat to intelligence, while Deception and Intimidation are commonly used NPC skills, Charisma didn't seem to offer up enough benefits compared to the other ability boosts. Looking at what all I already had for the other boosts I realized that I had bonuses to each save, bonuses to strike damage and to HP, but no bonus to spell damage which felt like a nice counterpoint to strike damage. Given that Charisma is the default ability for all innate magic, it felt like the most appropriate ability to house what amounted to a spell power boost. </p><p>Now of course having designed all these benefits I realized that any NPC with an ancestry would end up with a net benefit compared to an NPC without one, even discounting anything the creature got from the base ancestry or heritage. If we treat humans as the default, then all your human NPCs will be slightly weaker and more boring than other NPCs, to counteract this I added a human ancestry with a single boost that is roughly equivalent in power to the other Ancestry Templates.</p><p>If you were to apply the Ability Boost templates uniformly to all your NPCs there would be a small but noticeable uptick in effectiveness; based on my experience I'd suggest this uptick doesn't alter the effective level of any individual creature, but when applied uniformly to all NPCs it could, for example, take an encounter that was just below severe up to severe. For GMs who don't want that, perhaps especially GMs that are running Paizo adventure paths whose players may already be struggling with the difficulty a template with a smaller effect on the NPCs would be preferable, for that reason I ended up including the same templates, heritages and all but without any ability boosts, these will have a much smaller effect on encounter balance, at the cost of a little loss of verisimilitude.</p><p>Ancestry heritages were primarily based on the heritages listed in the Pathfinder Second Edition Core Rulebook for each of the six common ancestries. However, some of the heritages were difficult to automate in a satisfying fashion or otherwise were ill-suited to use on an NPC. To ensure there were an acceptable number of heritages available for each ancestry, additional heritages were invented that were inspired by a level 1 ancestry feat from that ancestry. </p></div></details></div>","markdown":""},"_id":"QibnMkhhPYrIrwG5","image":{},"video":{"controls":true,"volume":0.5},"src":null,"system":{},"sort":200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{}},{"name":"Credits & License","type":"text","title":{"show":false,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<div class=\"mmDemo-logo\"><img style=\"border:0\" src=\"modules/pf2e-mercenary-marketplace-demo/art/MM.png\" /></div><div class=\"main-box\"><h2 class=\"stylish\">Credits</h2><div style=\"margin-left:2em;padding-top:0.5em\"><p><strong>Authorship</strong> - Avery Rae</p><p><strong>Game Design </strong>- Avery Rae</p><p><strong>Graphic Design</strong> - Avery Rae</p><p><strong>Editing </strong>- Amanda</p><p><strong>Beta Testing </strong>- InfamousSky &amp; SkepticRobot</p><p><strong>The PF2e Foundry Team &amp; Discord Community</strong> - without the tireless efforts of which none of this could exist. I'm incredibly grateful for the amazing work everyone has put into the system, the questions you have answered, and the helpful resources and information I was directed towards while producing this module</p></div><h2 class=\"stylish\">License</h2><div style=\"width:90%;margin:0 auto\"><p>Pathfinder is a registered trademark of Paizo Inc. Pathfinder Second Edition and the Pathfinder Second Edition Compatibility Logo are trademarks of Paizo Inc. The Pathfinder-Icons font is © 2019 Paizo Inc. These trademarks and copyrighted works are used under the Pathfinder Second Edition Compatibility License. See <a class=\"href\" href=\"https://paizo.com/pathfinder/compatibility\">paizo.com/pathfinder/compatibility</a> for more information on this license.</p><h6>OPEN GAME LICENSE Version 1.0a</h6><p>    The following text is the property of Wizards of the Coast, Inc. and is Copyright 2000 Wizards of the Coast, Inc (\"Wizards\"). All Rights Reserved.</p><p>    1. Definitions: (a)\"Contributors\" means the copyright and/or trademark owners who have contributed Open Game Content; (b)\"Derivative Material\" means copyrighted material including derivative works and translations (including into other computer languages), potation, modification, correction, addition, extension, upgrade, improvement, compilation, abridgment or other form in which an existing work may be recast, transformed or adapted; (c) \"Distribute\" means to reproduce, license, rent, lease, sell, broadcast, publicly display, transmit or otherwise distribute; (d)\"Open Game Content\" means the game mechanic and includes the methods, procedures, processes and routines to the extent such content does not embody the Product Identi